SIMPLE: ticklish
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ticklish
<hw>Tic"klish</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Sensible
to slight touches; easily tickled; <as>as, the sole of the foot is very
<ex>ticklish</ex>; the hardened palm of the hand is not
<ex>ticklish</ex></as>.</def> <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Standing so as to be liable to totter and fall at
the slightest touch; unfixed; easily affected; unstable.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Can any man with comfort lodge in a condition so dismally
<qex>ticklish</qex>?</q> <rj><qau>Barrow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Difficult; nice; critical; <as>as, a
<ex>ticklish</ex> business</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Surely princes had need, in tender matters and <qex>ticklish</qex>
times, to beware what they say.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Tic"klish*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Tic"klish*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tickseed</ent>⟦br⟧
